Note that Stacy can always get a tweak to her money such that the total money she (\textit{total money} refers to the total amount of money she has after she comes out of the last shop) has doubled. To achieve this, let her final total money be $\alpha$. Assuming she's won all of her lottery games, the total money she has before visiting the last shop is $\frac{\alpha}{2}$. Once she visits the first shop, losing the $\1024$, she has $\frac{\alpha}{2}-1024$ dollars. She does this repeated $\left\lceil \log_2\left(\frac{d}2} \right\rceil + 1 \right\rceil = \left\lceil \log_2(d) \right\rceil + 1$ times. Thus the following holds: \begin{align*}\frac{1}{2^x}(d-2^{x+1}\cdot 1024) & \geq 0\\ 2^x &\leq d \\\Rightarrow x &\geq \log_2 d\\\Leftarrow \log_2(d) + 1 &\geq \log_2(d)\end{align*}
